name: Explore Buzzing Brixton from Colourful Bright Flat
description:
The entire property will be yours to enjoy

The management is done by a lovely local team - once a booking is accepted they will be in touch with the arrival time details and answer any queries you might have during your stay

Smack bang in the centre of South London, Brixton has become a go-to haunt for foodies, clubbers, artists, and rockers alike. Experience its sense of community with some shopping in Brixton Village or a drink with locals outside the Ritzy Cinema.

Electric Avenue is nearby and today, this narrow road is an open air market of fresh food and all the kind of goods you might need. Everything is immersed in its vibrating atmosphere.

Herne Hill is a 15 minute walk from the property so you can get to many parts of London in no time at all! There are also many buses in the area if you prefer!

*** LATE CHECK-IN FEE: PLEASE NOTE THERE IS A LATE CHECK-IN FEE OF £25 AS WE NEED TO ARRANGE TO MEET YOU AFTER HOURS. IF YOU PLAN

name: Stunning 1Bedroom Flat in Lincoln Plaza
description:
A stunning development in the heart of Canary Wharf, Lantern's Court contains stylish serviced apartments within proximity of London’s major business districts. The apartments are bright and spacious complete with a fully functional Kitchen.

Parking can be arranged on prior request and same will be on subject to availability upon booking.
neighborhood_overview:
Closely tied to big business and capital, Canary Wharf is a contemporary district located in the east of the London city. Ideal for corporate residents seeking a short commute to London’s business hubs, Canary Wharf is also a cultural center with a rich history. The history of the area is delineated in the Museum of London Docklands, which traces how the River Thames shaped the modern city.

Canary Wharf contains several retail districts. Jubilee Place, an underground shopping mall, contains an ensemble of boutique stores in addition to high street stores. Similarly, Cabot Place offers a collection of boutique stores. For dining, drinking and evening entertainment, Canary Wharf contains some of London’s most renowned restaurants and most sophisticated bars.

The apartment is right next door to ExCeL Exhibition, 10mins ride on the Cable car will take you to the O2 Arena, 5 mins ride to City Airport London and 1 min walk to the train station. The dock is also home to many different water activities such as wake boarding, and you can even hire a jetliner water jet pack.
neighborhood_overview: Royal Victoria is becoming a very popular destination because of proximity to ExCeL, quality accommodation, local amenities and transport links. ExCeL (Exhibition Centre London) is the largest exhibition centre in London, and the area now includes the longest cable car in the country, which takes you across the River Thames to the O2 Centre (formerly called the Millennium Dome). It is a spectacular way to arrive at any event there, or just simply try it for the amazing experience you cannot get anywhere else in London. Royal Victoria is also home to London's largest beach, where there are special events during summer.

name: SkyViews Apartment | ExCeL Centre | O2 Arena
description:
This delightful two-bedroom two-bathroom apartment is located in Royal Victoria Dock. A perfect location for your visit to London with many amenities and plenty of things to do.
The apartment is right next door to ExCeL Exhibition, 10mins ride on the Cable car will take you to the O2 Arena, 5 mins ride to City Airport London and 1 min walk to the train station. The dock is also home to many different water activities such as wake boarding, and you can even hire a jetliner water jet pack.
neighborhood_overview: Royal Victoria is becoming a very popular destination because of proximity to ExCeL, quality accommodation, local amenities and transport links. ExCeL (Exhibition Centre London) is the largest exhibition centre in London, and the area now includes the longest cable car in the country, which takes you across the River Thames to the O2 Centre (formerly called the Millennium Dome). It is a spectacular way to arrive at any event there, or just simply try it for the amazing experience you cannot get anywhere else in London. Royal Victoria is also home to London's largest beach, where there are special events during summer. There are many amenities in the area including several restaurants and a supermarket for all your self-catering requirements. If you need anything in particular, just let us know and we will direct you to where you can find it.

name: One bed lower ground floor flat in Fitzrovia
description: Beautifully furnished and with all the necessities for an enjoyable night in, these apartments are an easy, yet luxurious way to spend your stay in the city. Whether you are curled up on the sleek, black leather couch catching up on your shows with the complimentary Wi-Fi, or preparing a quick meal for yourself in the fully equipped kitchen, you’ll be as comfortable as if you were in your own living room. Follow up your long day with a relaxing bath in our lavish marble bathroom.
neighborhood_overview:
Fitzrovia offers visitors the diversity associated with London’s reputation, home to a variety of activities and industries equally sharing the space.

Located just north of Covent Garden, a few of its close attractions include The British Museum, Pollock’s Toy Museum, and the Grant Museum of Zoology. For those interested in exploring the night life, London Cocktail Club is known for its reasonably priced cocktails on Monday nights, and Charlotte Street is the hub for diverse cuisine and an array of bars, such as the historical Fitzrovia Tavern that gave the area its name.

If you’re in need of a bit of shipping, the Oxford Street shops are incredibly close by, giving you enough time to browse during the evenings and weekends. With Goodge Street station just around the corner of the apartment, you will have access to as much of London via the Northern line as you are prepared to experience throughout your stay.

Key Attractions

Spitalfields Market
Old Spitalfields Market is situated in the heart of Spitalfields and is a premier indoor market and retail attraction for all.

The market was built in 1876 and is one of the finest surviving Victorian Market Halls in the capital.

Nestled in the cobbled streets between Brick Lane and Bishopsgate, Old Spitalfields Market is steeped in history. Visitors will discover an array of themed markets, operating seven days a week, alongside boutique fashion, design and lifestyle stores, distinctive bars, coffee and tea shops and a wide range of restaurants.

The Royal Exchange
The Royal Exchange is a luxury shopping area in a historic building in the heart of The City.

You will discover an unrivalled collection of over 30 luxury stores that offer individuality and refinement second to none.

The boutiques include Gucci, Jo Malone London, Paul Smith, Tiffany & Co and Watches of Switze

name: Knightsbridge Executive One Bedroom Apartment
description: Not provided
neighborhood_overview:
Knightsbridge can be described in three words: wealthy, international and shopping. Located between Mayfair, Kensington and Belgravia, it’s one of the most exclusive residential and retail districts in west London and, of course, home to the world famous department store, Harrods. As well as shopping, Knightsbridge is renowned for its range of exclusive bars, restaurants and clubs to suit all tastes and attracts the rich, the royal and the celebrated from all over the globe.

Property prices in the area are sky high and although virtually in the heart of the city, residential streets are often located in quiet, tree-lined squares, tucked away from the buzz and activity of Brompton Road and Sloane Street. The architecture is imposing and mostly early 19th century red brick Queen Anne revival buildings or white stucco town houses by Thomas Cubitt (see ‘What to Do in Belgravia’) – wander the streets, absorb the cosmopolitan atmosphere and enjoy the shopping.

Cultural heartland with a touch of French
South Kensington is an affluent area often described as ‘London’s cultural heartland’. Two tube stations, Gloucester Road and South Kensington, provide excellent links to London’s entertainment, commercial/financial and political centres of the West End, City of London and Westminster.
The area houses three famous museums, a number of typically Victorian garden squares, the Royal Albert Hall, Imperial College London, the Royal Colleges of Art and Music and the Royal Geographical Society. name: Hyde Park Superior Three Bedroom Apartment
description: Not provided
neighborhood_overview:
Lancaster Gate is a mid-19th century development in Bayswater, west central London. It consists of two long terraces of beautiful houses overlooking Kensington Gardens and the adjacent Hyde Park.

The exclusiveness and grandeur of Lancaster Gate is offset with Bayswater’s vibrant cosmopolitan personality which typifies modern London. It is popular for its convenient and quick access into London, the theatres of the West End, the major business districts and famous shopping areas of Knightsbridge and Oxford Street. Paddington Station, the main transport hub, also offers a 15-minute Heathrow Express service.

Other interesting places within easy reach are Notting Hill made famous by the film starring Hugh Grant and Julia Roberts, its Portobello Market, the multi-cultural district of Edgware Road and the many and varied ethnic-cuisine restaurants in Queensway and Westbourne Grove.

name: Large Studio Apartment Near Kensington
description: As an aparthotel, Templeton Place offers all the benefits of an apartment with many of the perks of a hotel. All suites are designed and furnished with fully-equipped kitchens, beautiful bathrooms and sumptuous beds. Air conditioning in available in all suites and guests have access to a beautiful private garden. Our personalised and flexible service offers a level of comfort, convenience and attention to detail that is the hallmark of our family-run serviced apartments.
neighborhood_overview: Templeton Place is in gorgeous West London, full of stately homes and beautiful gardens. name: Home from home in Central London
description:
Set in the heart of Marylebone village, 56 Welbeck St is an elegant townhouse made up of seven spacious one-bedroom apartments.

Each apartment is outfitted to an exacting standard with Mid-Century Modern interiors and boast collectable artwork by the likes of Tracey Emin.

Our 24-hour concierge is just a phone call away to help with anything you may need and we will gladly meet you on arrival to assist with luggage and welcome you to your new home from home.
neighborhood_overview:
Marylebone is the quintessential inner-city neighbourhood. Shunning the big name brands and embracing independent boutiques, cafes and restaurants, it's truly one of London's most charming areas.

In your apartment, you will find our edit of our favourite places to eat, drink and be entertained in Marylebone.

description: Whip up a tasty brunch in the fitted kitchen of this beautiful designer one bedroom apartment. With a bright and comfortable aspect and dual windows, the fashionable interior boasts warm wooden floorboards and allows in plenty of natural light. Perfect for couples, this 368sq ft apartment benefits from free unlimited 150mb wifi and is a short 8 minute walk to the tubes in South Kensington.  CCTV, 24 hour porters, elevators and an office open Monday to Friday on the ground floor for assistance.
neighborhood_overview:
This landmark building was built in 1937 to provide luxury serviced accommodation to affluent residents, drawn to this prestigious area of London by the excellent designer shopping in fashionable Knightsbridge (Harrods) Sloane Street and the Kings (Chanel, Prada, Jimmy Choo etc) Road and its proximity to parks, arts and entertainment available in the area.

Home to members of the Royal family, Chelsea is the most exclusive part of town. Nell Gwynn House is just a 5 minute walk from both Sloane Square and South Kensington Tube Stations allowing guests to move swiftly and easily in and around London to explore this fine city. The west end and Theatreland is only 10 minutes away by tube and Canary Wharf, the business district, 15 minutes away.

The apartments are very well located and within walking distance for major visitor attractions such as the Natural History Museum, the Victoria and Albert Museum, as well as all the other museums to be found on Exhibition Road

neighborhood_overview:
With Chancery Lane Station and Holborn Station in such close proximity, the entirety of London is accessible right outside the doorstep of your apartment.

The area offers a variety of activities, attractive to both tourists and the locals, and perfect for those who fancy long weekend strolls. From shopping to sightseeing, Chancery Lane is epitome of city life and cultural experiences.

Holborn is home to the historic Temple Church with its magnificent architecture and beautiful organ recital as well as the Charles Dickens’ home, now converted into a museum. For those looking to shop, you can stop by Leather Lane Market for some delicious food or visit nearby shops pick up a few clothing or household gifts for your family and friends before your stay in London is over. Don’t forget to also work your way down to the river Thames or Covent Garden for a traditional experience of the city before you leave.

neighborhood_overview: Wesminster is home to two of London's most famous landmarks: The Houses of Parliament and Big Ben, both of which sit proudly on the river's edge. It is the centre of the country's political life, and so, perhaps unsurprisingly, it isn't London's hippest area - you'll be sharing the pavements with a mix of politicians and selfie-stick-wielding tourists. What it lacks in local colour or character, it makes up for in location - it's a great base for exploring nearby St James' s Park, Buckingham Palace, Mayfair, Trafalgar Square and beyond.

neighborhood_overview:
About the Area
Bayswater is well known for its close proximity to London’s greatest green space, Hyde Park. Its residents can boast a palace, lake and horse riding stables virtually in their front garden – and all in Zone 1. Its cultural and social mix, reflected in the amazingly varied restaurants and food stores that line up along Queensway, lends the area some unusual contrasts. Bayswater is cosmopolitan yet comfortable, cutting edge yet cultured. There's a strong sense of community here with a residents’ association and local magazine, and people tend to know their neighbours, a fact helped by the many shared garden squares. Historically famous for London’s first department store Whiteleys, and for having the highest concentration of hotels in London, the Bayswater of today is a much changed place. neighborhood_overview:
There's plenty of heart in Hackney, where high art and edgy innovation meet. There are flavours to savour from its lip-smacking restaurants, not to mention world-class coffees (Square Mile coffee beans, anyone?). Quirky, scruffy, sleek or hip – the area's bars and pubs suit whatever taste you're packing, as do its diversions (you're seriously spoilt for things to do). And if money's still burning a hole, Hackney's shops and markets sell temptation by the truckload, from vintage fabrics and designer must-haves to rare meats and artisanal bread.

Eating: There's an exceptional range of places to eat in Hackney, from the famous Vietnamese and Turkish restaurants on Mare Street, to newcomers such as Lardo, which serves pizza and Italian dishes. Broadway Market is also lined with popular restaurants and bars, and its busy Saturday stalls sell organic produce and offer all the latest street food trends.

name: Beautiful studio apartment in South Kensington
description: This modern studio apartment is situated in Kensington, just five minutes’ walk from Earl’s Court Station. It sleeps four with a king size bed and a two seater sleeper sofa in the living room, which easily transforms into a bed. The open-plan living/dining area and fully-integrated kitchen will make your stay a comfortable one. This apartment has a Nespresso machine and is equipped with complimentary linen, towels and toiletries.
neighborhood_overview:
You will be spoilt for choice in the stylish area of South Kensington. The neighbourhood is full of world-class local cafes, restaurants and bars. There is a great shopping area on the iconic King's Road- Chelsea, the famous Harrods in Knightsbridge and the trendy boutiques of Kensington High Street.

If you fancy a bit of green space, take a stroll to Holland Park in just 9-minutes, Kensington Gardens in 15-minutes or a little bit longer for Hyde Park.

For culture, visit the world famous Natural History Museum, the Science Museum, the Royal Albert Hall and Victoria & Albert Museum. Alternatively, have a short ride on the tube and you will find yourself in the theatre land of the West End, afterwards walk to Buckingham Palace, The Houses of Parliament, Big Ben and The London Eye.

SHOREDITCH is a world-famous, artsy and multicultural neighbourhood in Central London-- just a stone's throw to London's most iconic attractions (Tower Bridge, The Shard, The Gherkin, Big Ben, Houses of Parliament, etc.)

Immediately you’ll notice an “urban edge” in the street art, yet you’ll be in walking distance to world-class restaurants with skyline views (40th floor), musical venues, and the famous Jack-The-Ripper walking tours.

The neighborhood is both family-friendly and attractive to working professionals, as banks and companies like Amazon have set up in Shoreditch

Spitalfields Market
Old Spitalfields Market is situated in the heart of Spitalfields and is a premier indoor market and retail attraction for all.

The market was built in 1876 and is one of the finest surviving Victorian Market Halls in the capital.

Nestled in the cobbled streets between Brick Lane and Bishopsgate, Old Spitalfields Market is steeped in history. Visitors will discover an array of themed markets, operating seven days a week, alongside boutique fashion, design and lifestyle stores, distinctive bars, coffee and tea shops and a wide range of restaurants.

The Royal Exchange
The Royal Exchange is a luxury shopping area in a historic building in the heart of The City.

You will discover an unrivalled collection of over 30 luxury stores that offer individuality and refinement second to none.

The boutiques include Gucci, Jo Malone London, Paul Smith, Tiffany & Co and Watches of Switzerland.

neighborhood_overview: The creative hub of Clerkenwell offers a selection of quirky bars and restaurants and hosts a week-long festival devoted to design every May. At the weekend, you can make the most of the late-night spots on your doorstep or peruse the streets of Little Italy for somewhere to grab an authentic Italian lunch. Smithfield’s 13th-century meat market and London’s oldest surviving church, St Bartholomew the Great, are both only minutes from your apartment, giving you the opportunity to immerse yourself in the district’s rich history. Want to experience some of London’s more contemporary attractions? Visit the Barbican Centre’s exhibitions, concerts and film screenings or take a half-hour stroll along the A4, which will take you directly to Oxford Street, the West End and beyond. The nearest tube station is Farringdon, which is a 7-minute walk from the property.

name: Queens Park - 2 bedroom apartment
description:
Located on vibrant Salusbury Road, near shops, cafés & eateries. With the tube station just 5 mins' walk away, you can get to Regent’s Park, Notting Hill and Portobello Road all within 30 minutes.

• Bright, spacious open-plan flat with ample natural light
• Fully-fitted kitchen with washer/dryer and dishwasher
• Free Wi-Fi

We operate several fantastic apartments in this building. The photos are representative of a typical apartment but the exact unit allocation may differ to the unit shown.
neighborhood_overview: Queen’s Park is packed with Victorian and Edwardian houses clustered around the eponymous 12-hectare park, where you’ll find beautiful flower gardens, tennis courts, a golf course, bandstand, playground and paddling pool. Salusbury Road is undoubtedly the area’s community hub, offering a range of independent shops, cafés and eateries to explore. With excellent transport links, you’re well situated to get across the capital: Queen’s Park station is a four-minute walk away, with trains to Euston and Paddington, and the chic neighbourhoods of Kensal Rise, Notting Hill and West Hampstead are all easily accessible. Heathrow is a 45-minute drive away via the M4. A chic flat housed in a Grade II listed Georgian building on Gloucester Place, Marylebone. Just 4 minutes’ walk to both Marylebone and Baker Street tube stations, with London Zoo, Regent’s Park and Oxford Street all easily reached.
• Amenities include air-con, flat-screen TV, sofa bed and safe

neighborhood_overview: Gloucester Place is a short stroll from the Regents Park, where you can enjoy an open-air theatre, walk through rose gardens, or boat around the lake – or take a 20-minute stroll to the green expanses of Hyde Park. The Sherlock Holmes Museum, a 3-minute walk away on nearby Baker Street, is the official home of the famous fictional detective – step back in time to explore curios from some of Holmes’ most famous cases. Madame Tussauds, home to 150 celebrity figures, is around 7 minutes’ walk away. The Marylebone Theatre is a new performance space offering a programme of theatre, concerts and dance – but you can also reach London’s West End theatres within around 25 minutes via the tube. Marylebone High Street, a fantastic vibrant shopping destination with plenty of boutiques and big-name brands, is 11 minutes' walk away, while world-renowned Oxford Street is a short tube ride.

name: Clerkenwell serviced apartment with balcony
description: These stylish and beautifully decorated apartments at Leo Yard are amongst some of our most sought after apartments due to the incredible views over London they provide. Moreover, they are in a fantastic location with the nearest tube and railway station, Farringdon, on the Metropolitan, Hammersmith & City and Circle lines, being just four minutes to the south-west allowing you to explore the rest of the capital with ease.
neighborhood_overview: The creative hub of Clerkenwell offers a selection of quirky bars and restaurants and hosts a week-long festival devoted to design every May. At the weekend, you can make the most of the late-night spots on your doorstep or peruse the streets of Little Italy for somewhere to grab an authentic Italian lunch. Smithfield’s 13th-century meat market and London’s oldest surviving church, St Bartholomew the Great, are both only minutes from your apartment, giving you the opportunity to immerse yourself in the district’s rich history. Want to experience some of London’s more contemporary attractions? Visit the Barbican Centre’s exhibitions, concerts and film screenings or take a half-hour stroll along the A4, which will take you directly to Oxford Street, the West End and beyond. The nearest tube station is Farringdon, which is a 7-minute walk from the property.

Our Canary Gateway Apartments are located next to the busy financial area of Canary Wharf. Surrounded by glittering skyscrapers and bustling streets, you won’t run out of activities to fill up your time. With the Westferry DLR station only a few minutes away you will have access to a variety of boroughs throughout the city whenever you may need it.

For those looking to explore the area a bit more, take a trip the Museum of London Docklands for an interesting exhibition or visit Mudchute Park and Farm on the Isle of Dogs, home to rare breeds and farm animals.

Make the most of your stay in our apartments and experience what the London Borough of Tower Hamlets has to offer.

All in all, the area has more than everything to ensure your stay in Shoreditch is as relaxed and as fun as can be.

Liverpool Street is the closest tube and railway station, where you can get connections throughout the UK including to Cambridge and Brighton, as well as connections to the rest of the capital.

neighborhood_overview:
Welcome to Battersea!

Young professionals may be initially drawn to Battersea by its genteel way of life and flourishing café culture, but the area’s desirable Victorian and Edwardian properties provide a solid reason to stay. The rising popularity of Battersea in recent years has elevated every aspect of the area. From the local markets to green spaces, every space has benefitted from investment of time, money, and community energy.

Did you know?

Battersea Power Station

This iconic London landmark is now home to an exciting mix of restaurants, bars, leisure facilities and event spaces.


Historic significance

Settled as early as the Iron Age, Battersea’s Celtic history is evidenced by momentous artefacts, some of which are on display at the British Museum.


Famous fledglings

Cara Delevingne, Florence Welch and Prince George all attended the prestigious Thomas’s Battersea prep school.

Lancaster Gate is a mid-19th century development in Bayswater, west central London. It consists of two long terraces of beautiful houses overlooking Kensington Gardens and the adjacent Hyde Park.

The exclusiveness and grandeur of Lancaster Gate is offset with Bayswater’s vibrant cosmopolitan personality which typifies modern London. It is popular for its convenient and quick access into London, the theatres of the West End, the major business districts and famous shopping areas of Knightsbridge and Oxford Street. Paddington Station, the main transport hub, also offers a 15-minute Heathrow Express service.

Other interesting places within easy reach are Notting Hill made famous by the film starring Hugh Grant and Julia Roberts, its Portobello Market, the multi-cultural district of Edgware Road and the many and varied ethnic-cuisine restaurants in Queensway and Westbourne Grove.

As well as shopping, Knightsbridge is renowned for its range of exclusive bars, restaurants and clubs to suit all tastes and attracts the rich, the royal and the celebrated from all over the globe.

Property prices in the area are sky high and although virtually in the heart of the city, residential streets are often located in quiet, tree-lined squares, tucked away from the buzz and activity of Brompton Road and Sloane Street. The architecture is imposing and mostly early 19th century red brick Queen Anne revival buildings or white stucco town houses by Thomas Cubitt (see ‘What to Do in Belgravia’) – wander the streets, absorb the cosmopolitan atmosphere and enjoy the shopping.

Families are attracted by the great education options since there are fantastic primary schools, as well as a school that caters to children with autism.

description: Not provided
neighborhood_overview:
Lancaster Gate is a mid-19th century development in Bayswater, west central London. It consists of two long terraces of beautiful houses overlooking Kensington Gardens and the adjacent Hyde Park.

The exclusiveness and grandeur of Lancaster Gate is offset with Bayswater’s vibrant cosmopolitan personality which typifies modern London. It is popular for its convenient and quick access into London, the theatres of the West End, the major business districts and famous shopping areas of Knightsbridge and Oxford Street. Paddington Station, the main transport hub, also offers a 15-minute Heathrow Express service.

Other interesting places within easy reach are Notting Hill made famous by the film starring Hugh Grant and Julia Roberts, its Portobello Market, the multi-cultural district of Edgware Road and the many and varied ethnic-cuisine restaurants in Queensway and Westbourne Grove.

Cultural heartland with a touch of French
South Kensington is an affluent area often described as ‘London’s cultural heartland’. Two tube stations, Gloucester Road and South Kensington, provide excellent links to London’s entertainment, commercial/financial and political centres of the West End, City of London and Westminster.
The area houses three famous museums, a number of typically Victorian garden squares, the Royal Albert Hall, Imperial College London, the Royal Colleges of Art and Music and the Royal Geographical Society. Covering some of the most exclusive real estate in the world, it borders onto fashionable Knightsbridge, Chelsea and Kensington proper with their famous landmarks and shopping, including Hyde Park, Kensington Palace and Gardens and the shopping meccas of Harrod’s, Harvey Nichols and High Street Kensington.

description:
If you’re looking for somewhere to stay for a short or longer visit to the iconic city of London, we’d love to welcome you as our guest.

This tastefully decorated little pod is perfect for a solo traveller.

It’s clean, quiet, private, with its own shower and toilet.

Best of all, it is Centrally Located, opposite Harrods, the world’s most famous luxury department store.

Check in from 3pm
Check out by noon

name: Knightsbridge Deluxe Two Bedroom Apartment
description: Not provided
neighborhood_overview:
Knightsbridge can be described in three words: wealthy, international and shopping. Located between Mayfair, Kensington and Belgravia, it’s one of the most exclusive residential and retail districts in west London and, of course, home to the world famous department store, Harrods. As well as shopping, Knightsbridge is renowned for its range of exclusive bars, restaurants and clubs to suit all tastes and attracts the rich, the royal and the celebrated from all over the globe.

Property prices in the area are sky high and although virtually in the heart of the city, residential streets are often located in quiet, tree-lined squares, tucked away from the buzz and activity of Brompton Road and Sloane Street. The architecture is imposing and mostly early 19th century red brick Queen Anne revival buildings or white stucco town houses by Thomas Cubitt (see ‘What to Do in Belgravia’) – wander the streets, absorb the cosmopolitan atmosphere and enjoy the shopping.

neighborhood_overview:
Bloomsbury is a cultural and historical neighbourhood located in London's West End. It is home of the British Museum, the largest museum in the United Kingdom, and several educational institutions, including University College London and a number of other colleges and institutes.

Bloomsbury contains some of London's finest parks and buildings, and is particularly known for its formal squares, including Russel Square, Tavistock Square and Queen's Square to name but a few.

It is ideally situated for London's famous shopping district and West End Theatres and is a great base for exploring London.

description: Not provided
neighborhood_overview:
Knightsbridge can be described in three words: wealthy, international and shopping. Located between Mayfair, Kensington and Belgravia, it’s one of the most exclusive residential and retail districts in west London and, of course, home to the world famous department store, Harrods. As well as shopping, Knightsbridge is renowned for its range of exclusive bars, restaurants and clubs to suit all tastes and attracts the rich, the royal and the celebrated from all over the globe.

Property prices in the area are sky high and although virtually in the heart of the city, residential streets are often located in quiet, tree-lined squares, tucked away from the buzz and activity of Brompton Road and Sloane Street. The architecture is imposing and mostly early 19th century red brick Queen Anne revival buildings or white stucco town houses by Thomas Cubitt (see ‘What to Do in Belgravia’) – wander the streets, absorb the cosmopolitan atmosphere and enjoy the shopping.

neighborhood_overview:
Lancaster Gate is a mid-19th century development in Bayswater, west central London. It consists of two long terraces of beautiful houses overlooking Kensington Gardens and the adjacent Hyde Park.

The exclusiveness and grandeur of Lancaster Gate is offset with Bayswater’s vibrant cosmopolitan personality which typifies modern London. It is popular for its convenient and quick access into London, the theatres of the West End, the major business districts and famous shopping areas of Knightsbridge and Oxford Street. Paddington Station, the main transport hub, also offers a 15-minute Heathrow Express service.

Other interesting places within easy reach are Notting Hill made famous by the film starring Hugh Grant and Julia Roberts, its Portobello Market, the multi-cultural district of Edgware Road and the many and varied ethnic-cuisine restaurants in Queensway and Westbourne Grove.

Kensington is the ideal central London location with lots to explore, see and do: Royal Palaces, three world famous museums, green open spaces and parks, a famous concert hall, Imperial College, plenty of shopping opportunities, restaurants and cafes, and excellent transport links to theatre land in the West End and the city’s business districts.

name: Knightsbridge Executive Two Bedroom Apartment
description: Not provided
neighborhood_overview:
Knightsbridge can be described in three words: wealthy, international and shopping. Located between Mayfair, Kensington and Belgravia, it’s one of the most exclusive residential and retail districts in west London and, of course, home to the world famous department store, Harrods. As well as shopping, Knightsbridge is renowned for its range of exclusive bars, restaurants and clubs to suit all tastes and attracts the rich, the royal and the celebrated from all over the globe.

Property prices in the area are sky high and although virtually in the heart of the city, residential streets are often located in quiet, tree-lined squares, tucked away from the buzz and activity of Brompton Road and Sloane Street. The architecture is imposing and mostly early 19th century red brick Queen Anne revival buildings or white stucco town houses by Thomas Cubitt (see ‘What to Do in Belgravia’) – wander the streets, absorb the cosmopolitan atmosphere and enjoy the shopping.

neighborhood_overview:
Walking down New Cavendish Street you will find yourself on Marylebone High Street. This is a vibrant and chic London neighbourhood. It is home to a multitude of stunning boutiques, pubs and restaurants. If you’re in the mood for something bigger than the Marylebone boutiques, or you want to get out of the rain for the day, Selfridges is a 5 minute walk from the High Street. This iconic shopping centre is world famous and a place of pilgrimage for fashion enthusiasts around the world since it was founded in 1909.

The aura of Maylebone is varied. The view of well-dressed shoppers and picturesque mews houses may be disrupted by a vision of nurses on lunch breaks, or a doctor in scrubs grabbing a coffee. This is thanks to the time-honoured medical connections of Harley and Wimpole Street adjacent to the High Street. Here you will find some of the best private medical treatments and hospitals in the world

neighborhood_overview:
Stoke Newington, a quaint and vibrant residential neighbourhood, boasts a charming mix of independent boutiques, trendy global dining options, stylish cafes, and inviting bars along Stoke Newington Church Street. For a different flavour, the bustling High Street hosts a variety of local shops, kebab houses, and classic pubs. Nature enthusiasts can escape to the serene Clissold Park, replete with picturesque lakes, a skatepark, a spacious paddling pool, and a delightful animal enclosure housing deer and goats.

For those seeking convenience and transportation options, Stoke Newington offers access to several key train stations and the Underground. The Dalston Kingsland station is just 1.45 km away, with Canonbury and Hackney Central stations at 1.87 km and 1.96 km, respectively. Additionally, the London City Airport is a mere 8.6 miles away, while Heathrow Airport is conveniently accessible at 24 miles, making travel a breeze.

name: Shoreditch Boutique Private Studio
description:
Cute studio apartment located on Shoreditch High Street in vibrant Shoreditch; filled with colourful bars and restaurants among art spaces and active graffiti scene.

Free wifi, 1 towel per guest and linen are included.

Shoreditch is lively at night so some noise is to be expected but you are situated in the heart of the action with plenty to offer right on your doorstep!
neighborhood_overview:
You are right in the heart of one of the most colourful, vibrant and eclectic areas of London.

Famous for the Brick Lane Sunday market and interesting shops, bars and restaurants are spread across the neighbourhood for you to explore everyday.

Columbia Road Flower market is only a short walk away held on Sundays. Liverpool Street is a 14 minute walk which connects you directly to the centre of London.

Broadway Market is close by and runs every Saturday, it is worthwhile checking it out! On the way you will pass Spitafields market which is a great way to spend a few hours. It offers clothes, jewellery, vintage stalls, pop-up food vans and cafes.

We are situated in ZONE 1 which is central London but we are in the east side near Tower of London, St Pauls etc. We are not located near the West End (Covent Garden, Soho, Oxford st) but you will just have to catch a short train or bus ride there. London is very accessible and easy to get aro

neighborhood_overview:
Walking down New Cavendish Street you will find yourself on Marylebone High Street. This is a vibrant and chic London neighbourhood. It is home to a multitude of stunning boutiques, pubs and restaurants. If you’re in the mood for something bigger than the Marylebone boutiques, or you want to get out of the rain for the day, Selfridges is a 5 minute walk from the High Street. This iconic shopping centre is world famous and a place of pilgrimage for fashion enthusiasts around the world since it was founded in 1909.

The aura of Maylebone is varied. The view of well-dressed shoppers and picturesque mews houses may be disrupted by a vision of nurses on lunch breaks, or a doctor in scrubs grabbing a coffee. This is thanks to the time-honoured medical connections of Harley and Wimpole Street adjacent to the High Street. Here you will find some of the best private medical treatments and hospitals in the world.

A fashionable, affluent area, Holland Park is distinctive for its large Victorian town houses, exceptional restaurants and world-class shopping. Going out

Eating: Finchley is a centre of culinary delights with restaurants serving food from every region and culture, and it’s never difficult to find a kosher or halal eatery. For more traditional British fare, try the Two Brothers fish restaurant.

Drinking: The Old White Lion pub is perfect for a pint or two after a walk on Hampstead Heath, offering a selection of real ales as well as excellent pub grub. neighborhood_overview:
Walking down New Cavendish Street you will find yourself on Marylebone High Street. This is a vibrant and chic London neighbourhood. It is home to a multitude of stunning boutiques, pubs and restaurants. If you’re in the mood for something bigger than the Marylebone boutiques, or you want to get out of the rain for the day, Selfridges is a 5 minute walk from the High Street. This iconic shopping centre is world famous and a place of pilgrimage for fashion enthusiasts around the world since it was founded in 1909.

The aura of Maylebone is varied. The view of well-dressed shoppers and picturesque mews houses may be disrupted by a vision of nurses on lunch breaks, or a doctor in scrubs grabbing a coffee. This is thanks to the time-honoured medical connections of Harley and Wimpole Street adjacent to the High Street. Here you will find some of the best private medical treatments and hospitals in the world

Aptly named, Angel is a hallowed spot of London life. Thought to be a prime spot for the urban elite, it combines trendy bars and restaurants with unique market stalls and vintage shops. Its diverse range of entertainment appeals to a wide range of clientele, from the stylish fashionista to the art-house film buff. And live music is always available somewhere nearby.
Stretching eastwards towards the uber-hip streets of Shoreditch, and all the way down Upper Street, Angel is an eclectic and vibrant area. Its Business Design Centre is always buzzing with consumer fairs, while Camden Passage enables you to slip away into a hidden gem of antique stores and charming cafes.
There’s a reason why Angel is one of London’s most beloved social hubs. neighborhood_overview:
Situated in the east of London in an area undergoing tremendous change, Hackney Wick is a location with a rich industrial history that has now emerged as one of the most creative and dynamic communities in the capital. Home to an exciting and innovative arts scene, The Wick, as it has popularly become known has become a trendsetting area with a vibrant community of galleries, exhibition spaces and cafes, restaurants, bars and boutiques.

To the west, the wider borough of Hackney is a historic and dynamic area of London with bags of personality. To the east, just over the River Lea, the Olympics Legacy project is preparing to create up to 8,000 new homes and the largest new public park in Europe for 150 years on the site of the Games. Made up of Fish Island and parts of the Olympic Park a huge amount of investment has been made in this area over the past years achieving big infrastructure and transport advances and making this more and more of a hotspot within London.

description: This perfectly located two-bedroom apartment is all you need for both long and short stays in the city. A prime location with multiple transport options means you have the whole city on your doorstep, we hope you love it as much as we do.
neighborhood_overview:
A short walk from Borough and Southwark station, our apartment is a stones throw from one of London’s oldest and largest markets, Borough Market. You are spoilt for choice with an array of trendy coffee shops, quirky independent retailers, and some great spots to grab a drink. 7 days a week you can find a long line of food stalls offering cheap eats from all over the world.

Within a 20 minute commute you will find all of Londons biggest attractions. Southbank bursting with everything from art to food, Museums to aquariums, mini free music festivals at times and the world-famous London Eye there’s plenty to do. Views of Westminster, Big Ben, St Paul’s Cathedral and with a varying array of street performers there’s also plenty to see.

neighborhood_overview:
Vauxhall is one of the many London neighbourhoods that doesn't make it on the radar of most people.

Nonetheless, it has a great location on the Thames, a bustling town center, and offers a tight-knit community feel that you don’t find everywhere in London.

From Vauxhall you have an easy commute to just about anywhere. And after work, the riverside location provides a great space to clear your head on a waterfront run.

Fans of the recent James Bond movies will recognize one of the massive buildings here: Vauxhall is home to Britain's secret intelligence services.

Vauxhall is bordered on the north by Lambeth, on the east by Kennington, on the south by Stockwell, and on the west by the Thames.

name: Clerkenwell serviced apartment with balcony
description:
Sitting in a gated courtyard just off Clerkenwell Road, this apartment is a great place to stay in one of the trendiest areas of London. Visitors will be spoilt for choice by the variety of things to eat, drink, see and do nearby.

The apartment itself is as stylish as the area, having been decorated by our interiors team in a contemporary style, with modern furnishings and gorgeous artwork.

The apartment is also well connected into London, with Barbican and Farringdon Stations both nearby.
neighborhood_overview: The creative hub of Clerkenwell offers a selection of quirky bars and restaurants and hosts a week-long festival devoted to design every May. At the weekend, you can make the most of the late-night spots on your doorstep or peruse the streets of Little Italy for somewhere to grab an authentic Italian lunch. Smithfield’s 13th-century meat market and London’s oldest surviving church, St Bartholomew the Great, are both only minutes from your apartment, giving you the opportunity to immerse yourself in the district’s rich history. Want to experience some of London’s more contemporary attractions? Visit the Barbican Centre’s exhibitions, concerts and film screenings or take a half-hour stroll along the A4, which will take you directly to Oxford Street, the West End and beyond. The nearest tube station is Farringdon, which is a 7-minute walk from the property.

neighborhood_overview:
Notting Hill is so much more than just the setting for that famous movie: it plays host to the Notting Hill Carnival, Europe’s biggest street fiesta; it’s brimming with fashionable restaurants, pubs, bars and shops; it’s home to one of London’s best street markets: Portobello Road; and it’s got oodles of fascinating architecture and cultural history, including the Ladbroke Grove punk/reggae scene.

Attracting millions of visitors every year to its rainbow-coloured houses, enviable gardens and boho atmos, Notting Hill is the perfect place to spend a weekend exploring. Whether you’re into shopping, eating, cinema or just people-watching, it’s a great bit of London to lose a few hours (or even a few days) in.
